        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer296845743" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1724567035383088565">I had to come back and rate this story again. <br/><br/>I should have waited until I was done in the first place. Instead, I rated it half way through, giving it three measly stars no less. I&apos;ll never do that again. Boy, was I being miserly with my rating. It deserves five stars, and much more than that. <br/><br/>Stations of the Tide is a fantastic story. It was told in an original way, and it heightened my imagination. A story like this deserves awards. Michael Swanwick deserves applause. <br/><br/>In Stations of the Tide,</span>
  <span id="freeText1724567035383088565" style="display:none">I had to come back and rate this story again. <br><br>I should have waited until I was done in the first place. Instead, I rated it half way through, giving it three measly stars no less. I'll never do that again. Boy, was I being miserly with my rating. It deserves five stars, and much more than that. <br><br>Stations of the Tide is a fantastic story. It was told in an original way, and it heightened my imagination. A story like this deserves awards. Michael Swanwick deserves applause. <br><br>In Stations of the Tide, Mr. Swanwick paints a masterpiece with his vision of the future. His canvas is vast. His characters are raw, and they are tainted. But they are also all too human. Just like us they have desires. <br><br>Despite the fact that the main protagonist is only referred to as the bureaucrat throughout the story; I got to know him, and was rooting for him the whole time. I could not wait to see what happened next. <br><br>The world of Miranda, and the coming of Ocean. The bureaucrat and Gregorian. Magicians and Goddesses, sometimes known as witches. The Puzzle Palace. Proscribed technology. And so much more. This story was a treasure trove of grand ideas and high concepts, it blended genres together in such a way that I have never seen before. While at the same time it remained firmly planted in science fiction. <br><br>His descriptions of archipelago evoked fond memories in me, and had me longing for the islands of my birth. Every time they were mentioned in the story I found myself wishing I could go there. That same sense of nostalgia had me enthralled throughout my reading. It was powerful and pervasive, and oh so, entertaining. <br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/243859.Stations_of_the_Tide" title="Stations of the Tide by Michael Swanwick" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/photo.goodreads.com/books/1173069628s/243859.jpg" alt="Stations of the Tide by Michael Swanwick" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br><br><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/88/StationsOfTheTide%281stEd%29.jpg">http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia...</a></span>
